00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:39.070
Let's assume we
have n particles.

00:09:39.070 --> 00:09:42.105
And we have N possible states.

00:09:49.180 --> 00:09:57.060
And if it's a
classical system, let's

00:09:57.060 --> 00:10:04.270
assume we want to find one
particle in a certain state.

00:10:04.270 --> 00:10:07.220
We have a big box and want
to-- we have a big box,

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:08.990
have a small
sub-volume, and say what

00:10:08.990 --> 00:10:11.440
is the probability of
finding one particle here?

00:10:15.550 --> 00:10:21.960
So this probability
to find one particle

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:31.190
is P1 is small n over big
N. The probability to find

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:31.900
two particles.

00:10:34.550 --> 00:10:41.770
If you have non-interacting
classical particles,

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:43.670
well, it's simply P1 squared.

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:49.000
Independent classical
particles, they

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:50.560
don't care what they are doing.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:52.810
You grab into a
sub-volume, which

00:10:52.810 --> 00:10:54.220
is maybe phase space cell.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:55.770
And therefore,
your quantum state,

00:10:55.770 --> 00:10:58.360
you have probability
P of finding one.

00:10:58.360 --> 00:11:01.820
But since each particle
moves around independently,

00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:06.180
the probability to find two
particles is just P squared.

00:11:06.180 --> 00:11:08.566
It's a little bit like if
you toss two coins, one

00:11:08.566 --> 00:11:10.190
with your left and
one with your right,

00:11:10.190 --> 00:11:11.690
and you ask what
is the probability

00:11:11.690 --> 00:11:15.285
to find a head or
tail, and you simply

00:11:15.285 --> 00:11:16.410
multiply the probabilities.

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:24.880
But now, following reasonings
which Bose and Einstein

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:31.180
introduced, you want to use
counting statistics, which

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:33.860
takes into account the
indistinguishability

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:34.595
of particles.

00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:45.490
So if we go from the
classical distribution

00:11:45.490 --> 00:11:53.360
to the distribution of
indistinguishable particles,

00:11:53.360 --> 00:12:08.190
then the classical probability
P 1 is reduced by n factorial,

00:12:08.190 --> 00:12:19.040
because we are not--
let me put it this way.

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:20.805
The number-- I don't
want to go through

00:12:20.805 --> 00:12:23.040
a mathematical argument.

00:12:23.040 --> 00:12:33.240
If you grab one particle,
it can be the probability

00:12:33.240 --> 00:12:38.880
to find one particle
is represented

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:42.090
by a microconfiguration
classically.

00:12:42.090 --> 00:12:45.630
And each configuration
when you permute particles

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:47.500
counts as independent.

00:12:47.500 --> 00:12:50.180
But if you have quantum
indistinguishability,

00:12:50.180 --> 00:12:53.750
you're not counting
permutations as

00:12:53.750 --> 00:12:55.580
an independent configuration.

00:12:55.580 --> 00:12:58.325
And therefore, you have a
reduction by n factorial.

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:05.960
If you look at the probability
of finding two particles,

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:09.300
the reduction is-- this is
just the counting statistics

00:13:09.300 --> 00:13:12.100
n factorial by 2.

00:13:12.100 --> 00:13:20.500
So therefore, you will find
that classically, that quantum

00:13:20.500 --> 00:13:33.240
mechanically for
bosons, is two times.

00:13:46.990 --> 00:13:50.930
The probability to find two
bosons in one quantum state

00:13:50.930 --> 00:13:56.260
is two times the probability
squared to find one boson.

00:13:56.260 --> 00:13:57.845
So this is just
counting statistics.

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:09.870
This can be applied
to conditions

00:14:09.870 --> 00:14:12.350
in a Bose-Einstein
in a Bose gas.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.730
When you have inelastic
collisions, spin relaxation,

00:14:27.730 --> 00:14:34.620
dipolar collisions,
two body collisions,

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:37.560
two-body collisions
have a rate gamma 2,

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:41.280
which is proportional to
the probability of finding

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:45.297
two particles at the same
time at the same location.

00:14:45.297 --> 00:14:46.755
And that brings in
the g2 function.

00:14:49.300 --> 00:14:58.350
Whereas three-body
collisions, gamma 3,

00:14:58.350 --> 00:15:01.300
reflects the third
order correlation

00:15:01.300 --> 00:15:06.890
function g3, which is
defined in an analogous way.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:18.730
So if you now compare
at the same density

00:15:18.730 --> 00:15:25.060
the two-body rate coefficient,
like the same density

00:15:25.060 --> 00:15:29.340
means we are looking at the
rate of two-body collisions.

00:15:29.340 --> 00:15:35.630
And we compare between
two-body collision

00:15:35.630 --> 00:15:38.500
in a thermal cloud, which
is a g2 factor of two,

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:41.780
a thermal cloud of bosons.

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:43.660
Whereas a Bose-Einstein
condensate

00:15:43.660 --> 00:15:47.330
is a constant occupation
of particles in one mode

00:15:47.330 --> 00:15:51.670
and has therefore a g2 factor
of 1, exactly as [INAUDIBLE]

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:53.500
of the Bose-Einstein
condensate is

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:56.960
for particles for meta waves,
but the laser is for light.

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:03.040
Whereas, if you look at
three-body collisions,

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:05.730
those who do experiments with
Bose-Einstein condensates

00:16:05.730 --> 00:16:07.930
will know that
usually the lifetime

00:16:07.930 --> 00:16:09.589
of Bose-Einstein
condensates is limited

00:16:09.589 --> 00:16:10.630
by three-body collisions.

00:16:13.670 --> 00:16:18.290
Well, I didn't derive
it, but actually

00:16:18.290 --> 00:16:20.880
yes, we have the Gaussian
statistics for randomness.

00:16:20.880 --> 00:16:26.380
For Gaussian statistics, the
n-body collision function

00:16:26.380 --> 00:16:29.580
has a factor of n factorial.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:31.700
So therefore,
three-body collisions

00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:36.300
scale with 3 factorial, and
two-body collisions with 2

00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:37.930
factorial.

00:16:37.930 --> 00:16:40.090
So in other words, you
have a thermal cloud,

00:16:40.090 --> 00:16:43.180
you have a Bose-Einstein
condensate at the same density.

00:16:43.180 --> 00:16:45.470
But what matters for
two-body collision

00:16:45.470 --> 00:16:47.790
is not the average density.

00:16:47.790 --> 00:16:50.240
It is the average of n square.

00:16:50.240 --> 00:16:52.750
And the fluctuations
in the thermal cloud

00:16:52.750 --> 00:16:56.110
because of the g2 function
are two times enhanced

00:16:56.110 --> 00:16:59.290
compared to
Bose-Einstein condensate.

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:02.130
And therefore, you find
that at the same density,

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:03.047
you have more loss.

00:17:03.047 --> 00:17:05.380
You have a higher rate of two
and three-body collisions.

00:17:22.690 --> 00:17:30.280
Some of this was not--
became better understood

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:42.530
soon after Bose-Einstein
condensates were realized.

00:17:42.530 --> 00:17:45.950
The Boulder group studied
three-body collisions.

00:17:45.950 --> 00:17:54.350
And for two-body
collisions, myself

00:17:54.350 --> 00:17:57.210
in the post-doc
clarified the situation

00:17:57.210 --> 00:18:01.960
that even the mean field energy,
which everybody had measured

00:18:01.960 --> 00:18:06.490
before, requires two particles
to interact with short range

00:18:06.490 --> 00:18:09.930
interaction is therefore
proportional to g2.

00:18:09.930 --> 00:18:12.320
And therefore, when people
had determined the mean field

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:14.870
energy of a condensate
without really knowing

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:16.752
they had already
determined the g2 function

00:18:16.752 --> 00:18:17.960
of Bose-Einstein condensates.

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:34.880
OK, so this is pretty much
the counting statistic

