operator a1 you and a2.

00:20:04.390 --> 00:20:06.920
But if you are
asking what happens

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:10.580
if I measure two particles,
you annihilate two particles

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:13.300
with an operator a1 and a2.

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:16.130
But then, because of
the indistinguishability

00:20:16.130 --> 00:20:22.350
of particles, you
have to consider

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:27.600
an exchange term, which is a2a1.

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:29.440
So whenever you
detect two particles

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:31.520
in two different
modes, your signal

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:36.370
is proportional to something
related to a1a2 plus a2a1.

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:50.050
This extra exchange term
gives you an extra factor of 2

00:20:50.050 --> 00:20:55.140
for bosons, which is
exactly what appears

00:20:55.140 --> 00:20:58.760
in the g2 function.

00:20:58.760 --> 00:21:06.960
And, of course, if you have
an exchange term for fermions,

00:21:06.960 --> 00:21:09.930
you get 0.

00:21:09.930 --> 00:21:13.640
And this, of course,
leads to the antibunching,

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:19.610
or the g2 value
of 0 for fermions.

00:21:23.610 --> 00:21:36.450
However, and this is obvious,
if you have a single mode,

00:21:36.450 --> 00:21:42.470
then the only operator to detect
two particles is a1 times a1.

00:21:42.470 --> 00:21:44.910
And this has no exchange term.

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:55.560
And this is the
situation of the laser

00:21:55.560 --> 00:21:58.440
and the Bose-Einstein
condensate.

00:21:58.440 --> 00:22:02.870
And that means they
have a g2 function of 1.

00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:09.250
So Cory, this is
another argument

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:14.310
why single mode occupation
has a g2 function of 1.

00:22:14.310 --> 00:22:17.600
But I have to reconcile
