pretty much the same

01:00:38.730 --> 01:00:41.100
as the d dot e
term, because it's

01:00:41.100 --> 01:00:43.790
a bilinear product
of an operator which

01:00:43.790 --> 01:00:47.150
has an effect on the atoms and
has an effect on the photons.

01:00:47.150 --> 01:00:50.990
And it means you always switch
the quantum state in your atom

01:00:50.990 --> 01:00:53.430
and create or
annihilate the photon.

01:00:53.430 --> 01:00:56.380
But the a squared term--
it's just a square,

01:00:56.380 --> 01:00:58.350
it doesn't have a
p in front of it--

01:00:58.350 --> 01:01:06.820
will allow an atom in without
changing the state to create

01:01:06.820 --> 01:01:08.320
two photons, emit two photons.

01:01:08.320 --> 01:01:10.030
And then there's
probably a cross term

01:01:10.030 --> 01:01:12.700
which means to absorb
and emit a photon.

01:01:12.700 --> 01:01:17.547
You will actually, in one of
your next homework assignments,

01:01:17.547 --> 01:01:19.380
you will actually look
at the a square term.

01:01:19.380 --> 01:01:21.650
And I think it's a very
educational problem.

01:01:21.650 --> 01:01:23.375
So you really see
that you have two

01:01:23.375 --> 01:01:28.040
very different descriptions,
but the results fully agree.

01:01:28.040 --> 01:01:30.860
But this is already
an expert discussion.

01:01:30.860 --> 01:01:34.660
Why don't we for now just hang
onto the dipole approximation.

01:01:34.660 --> 01:01:37.070
We have d dot e,
and we just learn

01:01:37.070 --> 01:01:39.790
what is inside the
dipole approximation,

01:01:39.790 --> 01:01:43.400
and what is an exact quantum
mechanical description using

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:45.670
the dipole approximation.

01:01:45.670 --> 01:01:49.650
But and then we can come
back to the discussion,

01:01:49.650 --> 01:01:52.730
is everything we
describe really real.

01:01:52.730 --> 01:01:54.750
And while the answer
is, what is real

01:01:54.750 --> 01:01:57.350
in quantum physics
is the final result,

01:01:57.350 --> 01:01:59.570
the intermediate
results, you have

01:01:59.570 --> 01:02:03.380
to say that this is
only one possibility

01:02:03.380 --> 01:02:04.725
to go to the final result.

01:02:08.290 --> 01:02:23.765
OK, so we want to-- let me
just put in one more page.

01:02:39.740 --> 01:02:44.820
So what we want to do now is
we want to do a calculation.

01:02:44.820 --> 01:02:47.080
It's a perturbative
calculation, but we

01:02:47.080 --> 01:02:48.200
can take it to all orders.

01:02:48.200 --> 01:02:51.480
So therefore it's
exact and general.

01:02:51.480 --> 01:02:58.720
We want to do a perturbative
calculation of transition

01:02:58.720 --> 01:02:59.220
amplitudes.

01:03:07.660 --> 01:03:17.020
And what I am following here
the discussion in atom photon

01:03:17.020 --> 01:03:23.290
interaction on those pages.

01:03:23.290 --> 01:03:26.140
And the idea is the following.

01:03:26.140 --> 01:03:29.670
We have the Hamiltonian
for the atom.

01:03:29.670 --> 01:03:31.790
And then we have a
Hamiltonian which

01:03:31.790 --> 01:03:35.320
describes the transverse field.

01:03:44.380 --> 01:03:48.000
And the interaction of
the transverse field

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.690
with the atoms.

01:03:50.690 --> 01:03:55.920
What we want to use is we
want to use the interaction

01:03:55.920 --> 01:04:02.980
picture, which is often
the nicest picture

01:04:02.980 --> 01:04:08.380
to describe the effect of
the interaction between two

01:04:08.380 --> 01:04:10.570
systems.

01:04:10.570 --> 01:04:17.750
In the interaction picture,
you are transforming

01:04:17.750 --> 01:04:22.480
from you Schrodinger
type e function

01:04:22.480 --> 01:04:27.390
to wave function psi tilde.

01:04:27.390 --> 01:04:32.580
And those wave function
psi tilde include already

01:04:32.580 --> 01:04:35.860
the dynamics of the
Hamiltonian H naught.

01:04:43.620 --> 01:04:50.760
So that means that all operators
in the normal Schrodinger

01:04:50.760 --> 01:04:56.270
picture become now operators
in the interaction picture

01:04:56.270 --> 01:04:59.430
by canonical
transformation, which

01:04:59.430 --> 01:05:05.195
involves the dynamics due to
the unperturbed Hamiltonian.

01:05:10.850 --> 01:05:14.490
And so that's just
a reminder what

01:05:14.490 --> 01:05:16.610
the interaction picture is.

01:05:16.610 --> 01:05:20.800
And we are now interested what
happens in the interaction

01:05:20.800 --> 01:05:26.780
picture to an initial
wave function psi of ti.

01:05:26.780 --> 01:05:29.860
This wave function already
includes the time evolution

01:05:29.860 --> 01:05:31.610
due to H naught.

01:05:31.610 --> 01:05:35.240
So the only change now comes
because we have interactions

01:05:35.240 --> 01:05:37.220
with the electromagnetic field.

01:05:37.220 --> 01:05:39.950
So this allows us
now to focus only

01:05:39.950 --> 01:05:42.419
on the relevant interactions,
the interactions we

01:05:42.419 --> 01:05:43.210
want to understand.

01:05:51.190 --> 01:05:55.950
And the formalism which is
used in atom photon interaction

01:05:55.950 --> 01:05:58.530
focuses on the time
evolution operator,

01:05:58.530 --> 01:06:01.960
which I'm sure all
of you have seen.

01:06:01.960 --> 01:06:07.330
So the time evolution
of our system,

01:06:07.330 --> 01:06:09.510
how the wave function
involves from the initial

01:06:09.510 --> 01:06:14.990
to the final time, is described
by the time evolution operator.

01:06:17.930 --> 01:06:20.370
I will come back to the
wave function later,

01:06:20.370 --> 01:06:26.020
but in order to derive the time
evolution of the wave function,

01:06:26.020 --> 01:06:31.360
it's at least convenient
to focus first

01:06:31.360 --> 01:06:33.120
on the time evolution operator.

01:06:33.120 --> 01:06:34.700
So in other words,
I want to show

01:06:34.700 --> 01:06:37.850
you a formal solution for
the time evolution operator.

01:06:37.850 --> 01:06:40.800
And once we know the
time evolution operator,

01:06:40.800 --> 01:06:42.370
we apply it to
the wave function.

01:06:42.370 --> 01:06:44.619
And then we are talking again
about the wave function.

01:06:52.350 --> 01:06:58.140
OK, since the derivation
involves many equations

01:06:58.140 --> 01:07:02.050
and they are all printed in
the full beauty in atom photon

01:07:02.050 --> 01:07:08.970
interaction, I decided to
use pre-written slides here.

01:07:08.970 --> 01:07:12.530
Also, most of it is
fairly elementary.

01:07:12.530 --> 01:07:17.360
The equations are complicated,
but the concepts behind them

01:07:17.360 --> 01:07:19.540
are very, very simple.

01:07:19.540 --> 01:07:20.920
It's actually the
beauty of using

01:07:20.920 --> 01:07:22.490
a kind of a time
evolution operator.

01:07:22.490 --> 01:07:24.690
It's a little bit
mathematically formal,

01:07:24.690 --> 01:07:28.990
but it allows us to
express what is really

01:07:28.990 --> 01:07:32.160
going on in the solution
in very, very simple terms.

01:07:41.730 --> 01:07:44.460
So the goal is to do a
perturbative expansion

01:07:44.460 --> 01:07:47.300
for the time evolution operator.

01:07:47.300 --> 01:07:51.890
If we have no interaction
potential v, the interaction

01:07:51.890 --> 01:07:54.630
picture, nothing happens
in the interaction picture,

01:07:54.630 --> 01:07:56.380
and therefore, the
time evolution operator

01:07:56.380 --> 01:07:57.910
is a unity matrix.

01:07:57.910 --> 01:08:02.840
But if you have a coupling term
v, there is time evolution.

01:08:02.840 --> 01:08:05.130
And the time evolution
can be treated

01:08:05.130 --> 01:08:09.110
in lowest or in higher
orders in the perturbation.

01:08:09.110 --> 01:08:12.495
And we want to use now
perturbation expansion, where

01:08:12.495 --> 01:08:14.640
we have correction
terms, which is

01:08:14.640 --> 01:08:17.149
the first order, second
order, and nth order

01:08:17.149 --> 01:08:20.689
correction for time
evolution operator.

01:08:20.689 --> 01:08:22.790
So what we simply
want to do is we

01:08:22.790 --> 01:08:25.580
want to do an
iterative solution.

01:08:25.580 --> 01:08:28.130
We want to find an iterative
solution for the time evolution

01:08:28.130 --> 01:08:28.630
operator.

01:08:31.700 --> 01:08:34.240
The next two lines
is just a reminder.

01:08:37.080 --> 01:08:40.510
What is the differential
equation for the time evolution

01:08:40.510 --> 01:08:42.446
operator?

01:08:42.446 --> 01:08:45.029
Well, we are really just talking
about Schrodinger's equation.

01:08:45.029 --> 01:08:47.350
Schrodinger's equation
for the wave function

01:08:47.350 --> 01:08:49.850
turns into differential
equation for the time evolution

01:08:49.850 --> 01:08:50.979
operator.

01:08:50.979 --> 01:08:53.630
Schrodinger's equation in
the interaction picture

01:08:53.630 --> 01:08:56.970
says that the time
derivative of the wave

01:08:56.970 --> 01:08:59.310
function in the
interaction picture

01:08:59.310 --> 01:09:00.819
has nothing to do H naught.

01:09:00.819 --> 01:09:02.689
H naught has already
been absorbed

01:09:02.689 --> 01:09:04.710
in the definition of
the wave function.

01:09:04.710 --> 01:09:06.939
So the time evolution in
the interaction picture

01:09:06.939 --> 01:09:10.890
only comes from the
interaction term.

01:09:10.890 --> 01:09:20.810
And now, if you write the
wave function at time tf

01:09:20.810 --> 01:09:24.420
as the time evolved wave
function from the initial time

01:09:24.420 --> 01:09:29.600
to the final time, then you
take the derivative here.

01:09:29.600 --> 01:09:33.220
You actually take a derivative
of the time evolution operator.

01:09:33.220 --> 01:09:38.130
And therefore, in one step,
from Schrodinger's equation,

01:09:38.130 --> 01:09:41.609
you find a differential
equation for the time evolution

01:09:41.609 --> 01:09:43.710
operator.

01:09:43.710 --> 01:09:47.010
In other words, this is
now the operator equation

01:09:47.010 --> 01:09:48.880
for the time evolution operator.

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:53.640
And it's nothing else than a
100% rewrite of the Schrodinger

01:09:53.640 --> 01:09:54.140
equation.

01:10:02.180 --> 01:10:04.900
Interrupt me if
you have questions.

01:10:04.900 --> 01:10:08.580
This part should be--
we'll go through that

01:10:08.580 --> 01:10:10.400
for solely pedagogical reasons.

01:10:10.400 --> 01:10:13.920
And that means you should
really understand it.

01:10:13.920 --> 01:10:22.250
So this equation can
now be formally solved

01:10:22.250 --> 01:10:23.740
in the following way.

01:10:23.740 --> 01:10:27.310
Take this expression for
the time evolution operator

01:10:27.310 --> 01:10:31.790
and insert it in this equation,
and you find an identity.

01:10:31.790 --> 01:10:33.720
Of course, you haven't
really solved it,

01:10:33.720 --> 01:10:37.610
because you have the time
evolution operator expressed

01:10:37.610 --> 01:10:39.830
by the time evolution operator.

01:10:39.830 --> 01:10:42.150
This looks like a
circular conclusion,

01:10:42.150 --> 01:10:43.960
which is just nonsense.

01:10:43.960 --> 01:10:46.300
But if you inspect
it more closely,

01:10:46.300 --> 01:10:50.570
you observe that the time
evolution operator here

01:10:50.570 --> 01:10:54.260
is expressed by the time
evolution operator multiplied

01:10:54.260 --> 01:10:59.370
with v. And if you now think
in an iterative solution

01:10:59.370 --> 01:11:01.590
that we want to express.

01:11:01.590 --> 01:11:04.110
We want to expand the
time evolution operator

01:11:04.110 --> 01:11:09.320
in the different orders in the
interaction parameter v. Then

01:11:09.320 --> 01:11:15.250
you find actually
that if you are only

01:11:15.250 --> 01:11:19.210
interested in the first order
of the interaction operator,

01:11:19.210 --> 01:11:21.220
you can use the
[INAUDIBLE] order here,

01:11:21.220 --> 01:11:23.620
because you get one
more power of v.

01:11:23.620 --> 01:11:25.330
So that's how you
get the first order.

01:11:25.330 --> 01:11:28.610
If you want to know the second
order of the time evolution

01:11:28.610 --> 01:11:30.720
operator, you can
plug-in the first order

01:11:30.720 --> 01:11:32.150
on the right hand side.

01:11:32.150 --> 01:11:36.410
So therefore, you get
an iterative solution.

01:11:36.410 --> 01:11:38.710
The first order solution is one.

01:11:38.710 --> 01:11:41.120
The [INAUDIBLE] order solution
is the unity operator.

01:11:41.120 --> 01:11:45.120
The first order solution is by
just putting the unity operator

01:11:45.120 --> 01:11:45.890
here.

01:11:45.890 --> 01:11:49.220
The second order solution
is by taking the first order

01:11:49.220 --> 01:11:51.480
solution, plugging
it in in here.

01:11:51.480 --> 01:11:53.980
And then you get two
integrals over the operator

01:11:53.980 --> 01:12:00.100
v. So in that sense,
we have formally

01:12:00.100 --> 01:12:09.000
solved the time evolution
of the system in all orders.

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:10.524
So this is what
we get out of it.

01:12:18.120 --> 01:12:20.660
Yes, the equations
are getting longer.

01:12:20.660 --> 01:12:23.520
But the structure
is fairly obvious.

01:12:23.520 --> 01:12:30.970
So you saw that the--
let me just flashback.

01:12:30.970 --> 01:12:34.130
The first order term
had a temporal integral

01:12:34.130 --> 01:12:38.650
over v. The second order term
has two temporal integrals

01:12:38.650 --> 01:12:45.130
over v. And there's a time order
in between tau 1 and tau 2.

01:12:45.130 --> 01:12:52.370
And the nth order term now
involves n temporal integrals

01:12:52.370 --> 01:12:54.987
where the times are
ordered in such a way.

01:13:03.610 --> 01:13:07.940
Now we want to go back to
the Schrodinger equation.

01:13:07.940 --> 01:13:12.410
So we want to use this already
fairly complicated expression

01:13:12.410 --> 01:13:18.540
for the time evolution
operator and apply it

01:13:18.540 --> 01:13:20.860
to the initial wave function.

01:13:20.860 --> 01:13:22.880
And we want to calculate
matrix elements

01:13:22.880 --> 01:13:26.090
between the initial wave
function and some other phi

01:13:26.090 --> 01:13:32.670
f, some other wave
function in a given basis.

01:13:32.670 --> 01:13:43.380
So we are also going back.

01:13:43.380 --> 01:13:45.130
I don't want to go
through too many steps.

01:13:45.130 --> 01:13:49.270
Here, we're also going back
to the original Schrodinger

01:13:49.270 --> 01:13:50.010
picture.

01:13:50.010 --> 01:13:53.150
So I've taken all
the tildes off.

01:13:53.150 --> 01:13:56.140
But you know the step
form the Schrodinger

01:13:56.140 --> 01:13:58.590
picture to the
interaction picture

01:13:58.590 --> 01:14:01.740
was only taking out the
Hamiltonian H naught.

01:14:01.740 --> 01:14:07.880
And the Hamiltonian H naught
for eigenstates phi i and phi f,

01:14:07.880 --> 01:14:13.260
is simply a time evolution, e
to the e ei with a certain time.

01:14:13.260 --> 01:14:17.110
So all what this transformation
to the interaction picture

01:14:17.110 --> 01:14:21.080
gave us, it eliminated, at
least for a short while,

01:14:21.080 --> 01:14:24.210
all of those phase
factors, which are simply

01:14:24.210 --> 01:14:25.715
the evolution of
the eigenfunction

01:14:25.715 --> 01:14:26.840
in the Schrodinger picture.

01:14:47.460 --> 01:14:52.100
So let me look at a typical
term which we have right now.

01:14:52.100 --> 01:14:54.850
And you can't expect
something simpler

01:14:54.850 --> 01:14:57.325
than this, because this
is the general solution.

01:14:57.325 --> 01:15:00.200
It's an exact solution
to all orders.

01:15:00.200 --> 01:15:02.890
It's a summation over
terms to all orders.

01:15:02.890 --> 01:15:06.410
And eventually the summation of
an infinite number of diagrams

01:15:06.410 --> 01:15:09.270
is an exact solution.

01:15:09.270 --> 01:15:15.090
So what we've got here is we
have an integral over n times.

01:15:15.090 --> 01:15:17.570
And the n times
are time ordered.

01:15:17.570 --> 01:15:22.650
This is the formal solution for
the time evolution operator.

01:15:22.650 --> 01:15:30.950
And that means that we
integrate overall times,

01:15:30.950 --> 01:15:34.420
but what it is under
the integral sign

01:15:34.420 --> 01:15:39.290
is a product of the
operator v at times

01:15:39.290 --> 01:15:42.510
tau 1, tau 2, tau 3, tau 4.

01:15:45.230 --> 01:15:50.240
Since we got back to the
Schrodinger picture, what

01:15:50.240 --> 01:15:55.180
happens is between
times tau 1, and tau 2,

01:15:55.180 --> 01:15:59.370
the particle simply evolves
with the phase factor

01:15:59.370 --> 01:16:03.530
given by the
Hamiltonian H naught.

01:16:03.530 --> 01:16:05.540
So the picture is the following.

01:16:05.540 --> 01:16:11.030
The time evolution operator
in the interaction picture

01:16:11.030 --> 01:16:24.760
is a product over the operator
v tilde at different times.

01:16:24.760 --> 01:16:28.100
If you simply plug it back
into the above equation--

01:16:28.100 --> 01:16:30.110
and you have to look at
it for a little while

01:16:30.110 --> 01:16:32.810
to see that everything
works out correctly.

01:16:32.810 --> 01:16:38.785
But what that means is then that
if you go to the Schrodinger

01:16:38.785 --> 01:16:42.210
picture and write down the
operator in the Schrodinger

01:16:42.210 --> 01:16:44.900
in the basis of
unperturbed eigenfunction,

01:16:44.900 --> 01:16:50.900
that you have products of
the operator v at times

01:16:50.900 --> 01:16:54.510
t1, tau 2, tau 3,
they're time ordered.

01:16:57.590 --> 01:17:00.400
And because we have left
the interaction picture,

01:17:00.400 --> 01:17:04.400
you also get the propagation
with the phase factors

01:17:04.400 --> 01:17:07.850
given by the eigenenergies of
the unperturbed Hamiltonian H

01:17:07.850 --> 01:17:09.620
naught.

01:17:09.620 --> 01:17:12.480
So therefore, you get
just an infinite number

01:17:12.480 --> 01:17:16.840
of terms which have all
the following structure,

01:17:16.840 --> 01:17:20.830
that the particle propagates
in its eigenstate.

01:17:20.830 --> 01:17:24.770
It reaches a vertex where
the interaction switches

01:17:24.770 --> 01:17:27.520
the particle from one
state to the next.

01:17:27.520 --> 01:17:30.890
Then in the next state, which
may now be the excited state,

01:17:30.890 --> 01:17:33.850
we have propagation
in the excited state.

01:17:33.850 --> 01:17:37.560
Then the excited state is,
again, exchanging a photon,

01:17:37.560 --> 01:17:41.090
has an interaction term,
and is switched to-- well,

01:17:41.090 --> 01:17:43.880
for the two level system, it has
to go back to the ground state.

01:17:43.880 --> 01:17:47.740
In a more general situation, it
goes to another quantum state.

01:17:47.740 --> 01:18:02.160
So therefore, what we
have exactly derived

01:18:02.160 --> 01:18:06.640
is that the propagation,
or the time evolution,

01:18:06.640 --> 01:18:12.940
of the wave function
is nothing else then

01:18:12.940 --> 01:18:14.590
many, many of those factors.

01:18:17.490 --> 01:18:21.060
And each of those factors
can be represented

01:18:21.060 --> 01:18:22.460
by a diagram like this.

01:18:33.260 --> 01:18:42.410
So let me just write down
what this diagram here

01:18:42.410 --> 01:18:45.010
means mathematically.

01:18:45.010 --> 01:18:51.970
It means that initially, we
have a photon of energy epsilon,

01:18:51.970 --> 01:18:56.200
of polarization epsilon, wave
factor k, and a certain energy.

01:18:56.200 --> 01:18:59.080
And we have
particles in state a.

01:18:59.080 --> 01:19:10.970
That means that we get from the
initial time to the time tau 1.

01:19:10.970 --> 01:19:14.650
And tau 1 is the time
of the first vertex

01:19:14.650 --> 01:19:20.970
of the first photon exchange,
that the wave function evolves.

01:19:23.850 --> 01:19:28.800
And it evolves with an energy
of the unperturbed Hamiltonian,

01:19:28.800 --> 01:19:31.450
which is the atomic energy.

01:19:31.450 --> 01:19:33.510
And we have one
photon h bar omega.

01:19:36.160 --> 01:19:39.860
At the time tau 1--
and this is when

01:19:39.860 --> 01:19:41.560
the diagram on
the left hand side

01:19:41.560 --> 01:19:47.070
has a vertex-- we are now
bringing in the interaction

01:19:47.070 --> 01:19:50.880
operator, which
acts on the atom.

01:19:50.880 --> 01:19:55.100
